<figcaption data-index="1284"><p data-index="1285"><span class="figureLabel" data-index="1286"><b data-index="1287"><a role="doc-backlink" href="#c22-fig-0007-a" data-index="1288" data-section-index="32" data-section-idref="c22-fig-0007-a" data-target-data-index="986"><span style=" background-color: #226C7B; color: #FFFFFF;" data-index="1289">ILLUSTRATION 22.7</span></a> Lancer Financial Statements (LIFO)</b></span></p></figcaption>
</figure>
<p data-index="1290"><span epub:type="pagebreak" role="doc-pagebreak" title="22-11" id="Page_22-11" data-index="1291"></span>As <a href="c22.xhtml#c22-fig-0007" data-index="1292" data-section-index="32" data-section-idref="c22-fig-0007" data-target-data-index="988">Illustration 22.7</a> indicates, under LIFO Lancer Company reports $120,000 net income in 2018, $100,000 net income in 2019, and $87,000 net income in 2020. The amount of inventory reported on Lancer's balance sheet reflects LIFO costing.</p>
<p data-index="1293"><a class="blue" id="c22-fig-0008-a" href="c22.xhtml#c22-fig-0008" data-index="1294" data-section-index="32" data-section-idref="c22-fig-0008" data-target-data-index="1298"><b data-index="1295">Illustration 22.8</b></a> shows Lancer's income statement, retained earnings statement, balance sheet, and statement of cash flows for 2018–2020 under <b data-index="1296">FIFO</b>. You can see that <b data-index="1297">the cash flow statement under FIFO is the same as under LIFO</b>. Although the net incomes are different in each period, there is no cash flow effect from these differences in net income. (If we considered income taxes, a cash flow effect would result.)</p>
