<tbody data-index="3037">
<tr data-index="3038">
<td style=" vertical-align: top;" data-index="3039"><div class="left" data-index="3040">Retained Earnings</div></td>
<td style=" vertical-align: top;" data-index="3041"><div class="left" data-index="3042">50,000</div></td>
<td data-index="3043"><div class="left" data-index="3044">&nbsp;</div></td>
</tr>
<tr data-index="3045">
<td style=" vertical-align: top;" data-index="3046"><div class="left" data-index="3047"> &nbsp;&nbsp;Rent Revenue</div></td>
<td data-index="3048"><div class="left" data-index="3049">&nbsp;</div></td>
<td style=" vertical-align: top;" data-index="3050"><div class="left" data-index="3051">50,000</div></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</figure>
<p data-index="3052"><b data-index="3053">If Hurley has closed the books for 2021, it makes no entry because the error is counterbalanced.</b></p>
</section>
<section id="c22-sec-0159" data-index="3054">
<h5 class="grey" data-index="3055">Overstatement of Accrued Revenue</h5>
<p data-index="3056">On December 31, 2020, Hurley Enterprises accrued as interest revenue $8,000 that applied to 2021. On that date, the company recorded a debit to Interest Receivable and a credit to Interest Revenue. The entry on December 31, 2021, to correct for this error, assuming that Hurley has not closed the books for 2021, is:</p>
<figure data-index="3057">
<table data-index="3058">
