</tbody>
</table>
</figure>
<p data-index="3096"><b data-index="3097">If Hurley has closed the books for 2021, it makes no entry because the error is counterbalanced.</b></p>
</section>
</section>
<section id="c22-sec-0161" data-index="3098">
<h4 class="codeColorBlue2" data-index="3099">Noncounterbalancing Errors</h4>
<p data-index="3100">The entries for noncounterbalancing errors are more complex. Companies must make correcting entries, even if they have closed the books.</p>
<section id="c22-sec-0162" data-index="3101">
<h5 class="grey" data-index="3102">Failure to Record Depreciation</h5>
<p data-index="3103">Assume that on January 1, 2020, Hurley Enterprises purchased a machine for $10,000 that had an estimated useful life of five years. The accountant incorrectly expensed this machine in 2020, but discovered the error in 2021. If we assume that Hurley uses straight-line depreciation on this asset, the entry on December 31, 2021, to correct for this error, given that Hurley has or has not closed the books, is as follows.</p>
<figure data-index="3104">
<table class="table tbc" data-index="3105">
<tbody data-index="3106">
<tr data-index="3107">
<td colspan="3" style=" vertical-align: bottom;" data-index="3108"><p class="center" style=" border: 1px solid black; background-color: #FFFFFF;" data-index="3109"><b data-index="3110">Hurley has not closed the books for 2021:</b></p></td>
</tr>
<tr data-index="3111">
<td style=" vertical-align: top;" data-index="3112"><div class="left" data-index="3113">Equipment</div></td>
<td style=" vertical-align: top;" data-index="3114"><div class="right" data-index="3115">10,000</div></td>
<td data-index="3116"><div class="right" data-index="3117">&nbsp;</div></td>
