<section id="c22-sec-0167" data-index="3365">
<h3 data-index="3366"><span class="red" data-index="3367">Comprehensive Example: Numerous Errors</span></h3>
<p data-index="3368">In some circumstances, a combination of errors occurs. The company therefore prepares a worksheet to facilitate the analysis. The following problem demonstrates use of the worksheet. The mechanics of its preparation should be obvious from the solution format. The income statements of Hudson Company for the years ended December 31, 2019, 2020, and 2021, indicate the following net incomes.</p>
<figure data-index="3369">
<table data-index="3370">
<tbody data-index="3371">
<tr data-index="3372">
<td style=" vertical-align: top;" data-index="3373"><div class="left" data-index="3374">2019</div></td>
<td style=" vertical-align: top;" data-index="3375"><div class="right" data-index="3376">$17,400</div></td>
</tr>
<tr data-index="3377">
<td style=" vertical-align: top;" data-index="3378"><div class="left" data-index="3379">2020</div></td>
<td style=" vertical-align: top;" data-index="3380"><div class="right" data-index="3381">20,200</div></td>
</tr>
<tr data-index="3382">
<td style=" vertical-align: top;" data-index="3383"><div class="left" data-index="3384">2021</div></td>
<td style=" vertical-align: top;" data-index="3385"><div class="right" data-index="3386">11,300</div></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</figure>
<p data-index="3387">An examination of the accounting records for these years indicates that Hudson Company made several errors in arriving at the net income amounts reported:</p>
<ul class="none" id="c22-list-0168" data-index="3388">
<li data-index="3389"><b data-index="3390">1.</b> The company consistently omitted from the records wages earned by workers but not paid at December 31. The amounts omitted were:
<figure data-index="3391">
<table data-index="3392">
<tbody data-index="3393">
<tr data-index="3394">
<td style=" vertical-align: top;" data-index="3395"><div class="left" data-index="3396">December 31, 2019</div></td>
<td style=" vertical-align: top;" data-index="3397"><div class="right" data-index="3398">$1,000</div></td>
</tr>
<tr data-index="3399">
<td style=" vertical-align: top;" data-index="3400"><div class="left" data-index="3401">December 31, 2020</div></td>
<td style=" vertical-align: top;" data-index="3402"><div class="right" data-index="3403">1,400</div></td>
</tr>
<tr data-index="3404">
<td style=" vertical-align: top;" data-index="3405"><div class="left" data-index="3406">December 31, 2021</div></td>
<td style=" vertical-align: top;" data-index="3407"><div class="right" data-index="3408">1,600</div></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</figure>
<p data-index="3409">When paid in the year following that in which they were earned, Hudson recorded these amounts as expenses.</p></li>
<li data-index="3410"><span epub:type="pagebreak" role="doc-pagebreak" title="22-29" id="Page_22-29" data-index="3411"></span><b data-index="3412">2.</b> The company overstated merchandise inventory on December 31, 2019, by $1,900 as the result of errors made in the footings and extensions on the inventory sheets.</li>
<li data-index="3413"><b data-index="3414">3.</b> On December 31, 2020, Hudson expensed prepaid insurance of $1,200, applicable to 2021.</li>
<li data-index="3415"><b data-index="3416">4.</b> The company did not record on December 31, 2020, interest receivable in the amount of $240.</li>
<li data-index="3417"><b data-index="3418">5.</b> On January 2, 2020, Hudson sold for $1,800 a piece of equipment costing $3,900. At the date of sale, the equipment had accumulated depreciation of $2,400. The company recorded the cash received as Miscellaneous Income in 2020. In addition, the company continued to record depreciation for this equipment in both 2020 and 2021 at the rate of 10 percent of cost.</li>
</ul>
<p data-index="3419">The first step in preparing the worksheet is to prepare a schedule showing the reported net income amounts for the years ended December 31, 2019, 2020, and 2021. Each correction of the amount originally reported is clearly labeled. The next step is to indicate the balance sheet accounts affected as of December 31, 2021. <a class="blue" id="c22-fig-0024-a" href="c22.xhtml#c22-fig-0024" data-index="3420" data-section-index="32" data-section-idref="c22-fig-0024" data-target-data-index="3422"><b data-index="3421">Illustration 22.24</b></a> shows the completed worksheet for Hudson Company.</p>
<figure id="c22-fig-0024" data-index="3422">
<img src="https://ereader-books-prod.chegg.com/682/9781119503682/39c53495-be04-40a4-af01-80a39a7df223/OPS/images/c22/w0844.jpg" alt="A screenshot of a spreadsheet shows errors in the income statement and balance sheet, The report begins with a two-line heading displaying the name of the company, Hudson Company, and the type of statement, Worksheet to correct income and balance sheet errors. There are 8 columns with the first containing a list of errors. Columns 2 through 5 are collectively labeled as worksheet analysis of changes in net income with four sub-columns labeled with the three years impacted by the errors, 2019, 2020, 2021, and the totals. The next three columns are labeled as balance sheet corrections at December 31, 2021 with three sub-columns, debit, credit, and account. The data presented in the table follow:
Net income as reported is displayed as $17,400 for 2019; $20,200 for 2020; $11,300 for 2021; and a total of $48,900. 
The first adjustment is for wages unpaid at December 31, 2019, with a decrease of $1,000 to net income in 2019 and an increase of 1,000 in net income for 2020, resulting in total of 0. 
The second adjustment is for wages unpaid at December 31, 2020, with a decrease of $1,400 in 2020 and an increase of 1,400 in net income for 2022, resulting in total of 0. 
The third adjustment is for wages unpaid at December 31, 2021, with a decrease of $1,600 in 2021 resulting in a total decrease in net income of 1,600. This error requires a credit of $1,600 to salaries and wages payable of $1,600. 
The next error is an inventory overstatement at December 31, 2019 with a decrease of $1,900 in net income for 2019 and an increase of 1,900 in net income for 2020, resulting in total of 0. 
The next error is for prepaid insurance at December 31, 2020 with an increase of $1,200 in net income for 2020 and a decrease of 1,200 in net income for 2021, resulting in total of 0.
The next error is for interest receivable at December 31, 2020 with an increase of $240 in net income for 2020 and a decrease of 240 in net income for 2021, resulting in total of 0.
A correction for an entry made upon the sale of equipment dated January 2, 2020 shows a decrease of $1,500 to net income in 2020 and a total decrease of 1,500. This results in a debit for $2,400 to Accumulated Depreciation Equipment, and a credit of $3,900 to Equipment. The calculation is shown as a note as the cost of $3,900 less accumulated depreciation of 2,400 equals the book value of 1,500. The proceeds from the sale of 1,800 are subtracted from the book value to arrive at a gain on sale of $300. The income reported is reduced by $1,800, resulting in the $1,500 decrease to net income for 2020. 
An error for an overcharge of depreciation at December 31, 2020 shows an increase of $390 in net income for 2020, a total increase to net income of $390, and a debit to accumulated depreciation equipment. An error for an overcharge of depreciation at December 31, 2021 shows an increase of $390 in net income for 2021, a total increase to net income of $390, and a debit to accumulated depreciation equipment. 
The corrected net income is $14,500 for 2019, $22,030 for 2020, $10,050 for 2021, and $46,580 as the total net income impact." data-index="3423" data-size="%7B%22width%22%3A1051%2C%22height%22%3A849%7D">
<figcaption data-index="3424"><p data-index="3425"><span class="figureLabel" data-index="3426"><b data-index="3427"><a role="doc-backlink" href="#c22-fig-0024-a" data-index="3428" data-section-index="32" data-section-idref="c22-fig-0024-a" data-target-data-index="3420"><span style=" background-color: #226C7B; color: #FFFFFF;" data-index="3429">ILLUSTRATION 22.24</span></a> Worksheet to Correct Income and Balance Sheet Errors</b></span></p></figcaption>
</figure>
<p data-index="3430"><span epub:type="pagebreak" role="doc-pagebreak" title="22-30" id="Page_22-30" data-index="3431"></span>The correcting entries on December 31, 2021, assuming the books have not or have been closed, are as follows.</p>
<figure data-index="3432">
<table class="table tbc" data-index="3433">
